    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided S-1 preamble and MD&A chunks, here are the specific figures and language regarding Falcon 9 launch costs, reusability, internal Starlink launch costs, and the cost advantage of vertical integration:\n\n### 1. Launch Costs and Reusability Economics\nThe document emphasizes that reusing hardware is the central driver of SpaceX\'s launch economics, significantly lowering costs compared to historical averages and expendable systems.\n\n**Specific Cost Figures & Reductions:**\n*   **Historical Average:** The historical average launch cost was $18,500 per kilogram.\n*   **Falcon 9 (2010):** The first version of Falcon 9 reduced launch cost to approximately $2,700 per kilogram—an approximate 85% reduction compared to the historical average.\n*   **Falcon Heavy (2018):** Further reduced costs to approximately $1,400 per kilogram, a 92% reduction compared to the historical average.\n*   **Overall Cost Reduction:** Partial reusability for orbital spaceflight has reduced the cost per ton to orbit by approximately 85%.\n*   **Future Projections (Starship):** With the future deployment of Starship, the company aims to reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more relative to the historical average.\n*   **Macro Impact:** "Space flight that historically cost billions per launch now costs in the tens of millions, fundamentally reducing the cost of space access..."\n\n**Language on Reusability & Cost Structure:**\n*   **Lower Marginal Costs:** "Reuse of the first-stage—representing the majority of vehicle manufacturing cost—has materially reduced marginal launch costs relative to fully expendable systems."\n*   **Spreading Fixed Costs:** "Central to our cost advantage is the reusability of key hardware—most notably boosters—which we recover, refurbish, and refly many times instead of discarding after single use. This dramatically lowers per-launch costs by minimizing hardware replacement expenses and spreading fixed production costs across repeated uses."\n*   **Accounting Treatment:** Boosters, fairings, and Merlin engines are classified as property, plant, and equipment (PP&E) and depreciated to cost of revenue. The second stage is not reusable and is expensed to cost of revenue upon launch.\n*   **Booster Lifespan:** Falcon 9 boosters have been engineered and demonstrated to support up to 40 flights. However, SpaceX has established a maximum accounting useful life of 25 flights based on forecasted utilization, the strategic transition to Starship, and government contract restrictions (which prohibit using boosters flown more than five times).\n\n**Financial Impact of Reusability (MD&A):**\n*   **2025 Impact:** Cost of revenue for the Space segment decreased by $189 million (12.2%) compared to 2024, primarily due to increased reusability resulting in lower depreciation of $240 million.\n*   **2024 Impact:** Cost of revenue decreased by $128 million (7.6%) compared to 2023, primarily due to increased reusability resulting in lower depreciation of $80 million.\n\n### 2. Internal Launch Costs for Starlink\nThe S-1 clarifies how internal Starlink launches are treated financially, highlighting that these costs are capitalized rather than expensed immediately in the Space segment.\n\n*   **Capitalization Policy:** "For launches dedicated to deploying our Starlink satellites, we capitalize the associated costs within our Connectivity segment and depreciate them over time, and we do not recognize revenue for those launches in our Space segment."\n*   **Impact on Space Segment Cost of Revenue:** The relative increase in Starlink satellite launches shifts overhead costs out of the Space segment and into the Connectivity segment.\n    *   In 2025, Starlink launches increased from 89 to 122, resulting in relatively more launch operations and overhead costs capitalized in the Connectivity segment ($14 million).\n    *   In 2024, Starlink launches increased from 63 to 89, resulting in $99 million of launch operations and overhead costs being capitalized in the Connectivity segment.\n\n### 3. Cost Advantage of Vertical Integration\nThe preamble explicitly links the company\'s cost efficiency and speed to its extreme vertical integration and end-to-end control over the value chain.\n\n*   **End-to-End Control:** "Our extensive vertical integration and end-to-end control over the entire value chain, from design to launch to operations, allows us to achieve unprecedented speed and cost efficiency."\n*   **Industry Disruption:** "Since our founding in 2002, SpaceX has cracked the code on accessing space at scale, transforming an industry characterized by decades of stagnation, risk aversion, and economically perverse cost structures."\n*   **Foundational Philosophy:** "on extreme vertical integration have propelled us to achieve what many deemed impossible. We have demonstrated the ability to achieve groundbreaking technological innovations with speed, quality control, and precision."',
