2026-06-25 01:37:42,136 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Assessment: Starlink\'s Self-Funding Capacity vs. Eutelsat\'s Externally-Financed Constellation Refresh\n\n### 1. SpaceX Connectivity Segment FY2025 Cash Generation Profile (from S-1)\n\nPer the recast consolidated S-1 (which includes xAI and X Holdings for all periods presented), the Connectivity (Starlink) segment reported the following for FY2025:\n\n| Metric (FY2025) | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| Connectivity Segment Revenue | $11,387M |\n| Connectivity Segment Income from Operations | $4,423M |\n| (+) Depreciation & Amortization | $2,376M |\n| (+) Share-based compensation | $369M |\n| **Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$7,168M** |\n| **Connectivity Segment Capex** | **$4,178M** |\n| **EBITDA − Capex (FCF proxy)** | **$2,990M** |\n\nFor context, Connectivity Adjusted EBITDA grew from $1,602M (FY2023) → $3,849M (FY2024) → $7,168M (FY2025), an 86% YoY growth rate, while Connectivity capex grew more slowly ($2,455M → $3,498M → $4,178M, ~19% YoY in 2025). The segment is therefore not only large but expanding its cash conversion.\n\n### 2. Eutelsat\'s Funding Structure for the 440-Satellite Refresh\n\nEutelsat\'s OneWeb Gen-1 replenishment program (440 satellites ordered from Airbus, deliveries beginning late 2026) carries an estimated total cost of **€2.2 billion (≈ $2.56 billion at ~1.16 EUR/USD)** spread over 2024–2029 — i.e., roughly **€440M (~$512M) per year** over five years. (Note: the question\'s phrasing of "€2.56 billion" appears to conflate the euro-denominated program cost of €2.2B with its USD-equivalent of ~$2.56B; the underlying program size is €2.2B.)\n\nTo execute this program, Eutelsat required a layered external financing structure:\n\n| Funding Component | Amount | Source / Character |\n|---|---|---|\n| Equity capital raise (H1 FY2025-26) | €1.5B | French State (stake to ~29.65%), UK, Bharti, CMA CGM, FSP — significant dilution / state ownership |\n| Government-backed export credit financing (Feb 2026) | ~€1.0B | French government-guaranteed, dedicated to LEO satellites |\n| Bond refinancing | €1.5B | Replaced higher-cost debt |\n| **Result: Net debt halved** | €2.6B → €1.3B | Net debt/EBITDA from 3.88x → ~2.00x |\n| **Credit rating upgrades required** | Moody\'s: B1 → Ba3; Fitch: B/CCC+ → BB | Triggered by the raise |\n\nEutelsat\'s standalone EBITDA is approximately **€650–670M** (implied from net debt/EBITDA ratios), against which the €2.2B program represents **~3.3x annual EBITDA** — a multi-year commitment that could not be absorbed internally and required sovereign-backed support and rating actions to make viable.\n\n### 3. Could Starlink Self-Fund an Equivalent Refresh at Current Run-Rates?\n\n**Yes — and by a wide margin.** Using SpaceX\'s disclosed FY2025 Connectivity figures:\n\n- **Annual FCF proxy (EBITDA − Capex): $2,990M**\n- **Eutelsat-equivalent annual program cost: ~$512M/year** (€2.2B / 5 years)\n- **Coverage ratio: $2,990M / $512M ≈ 5.8x**\n\nEven on a total-program basis, **one year of Connectivity-segment free cash flow ($2,990M) covers 117% of the entire $2.56B Eutelsat program** ($2,990M / $2,560M = 1.17x). Put differently, Starlink\'s FY2025 cash generation after capex could fund the *entire* 440-satellite OneWeb refresh in under 11 months — without touching the $24.7B of consolidated cash on the balance sheet, without issuing equity, and without sovereign credit support.\n\nThis comparison is, if anything, conservative because:\n- SpaceX is *already* refreshing its constellation at a far higher cadence: **~3,100 Starlink satellites launched in 2025** (vs. Eutelsat\'s 440 over five years), with a Redmond production line running at **~70 satellites/week (~3,640/year)**.\n- The $4,178M of Connectivity capex in FY2025 *already includes* the cost of manufacturing and internally launching those 3,100 satellites (the S-1 confirms Starlink-dedicated launch costs are capitalized within the Connectivity segment, not recognized as Space-segment revenue). The $2,990M FCF proxy is therefore *after* funding a refresh rate roughly **7x faster** than Eutelsat\'s planned program.\n- SpaceX\'s constellation is ~9,600 satellites (≈75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit) versus OneWeb\'s ~648 — meaning Starlink\'s refresh burden in absolute terms is far larger, yet is absorbed entirely within segment cash flow.\n\n### 4. What the Contrast Reveals About Starlink\'s Competitive Moat\n\nThe funding-structure divergence between the two operators isolates three reinforcing layers of Starlink\'s moat:\n\n**(a) Scale of cash generation.** SpaceX\'s Connectivity segment alone generated **$7,168M of Adjusted EBITDA in FY2025** — roughly **10.7x Eutelsat\'s total company EBITDA (~€670M)** — off a 10.3M-subscriber base across 164 markets. This revenue scale (driven by 104.7% subscriber growth, partially offset by 22.9% ARPU decline from international expansion) produces operating cash flow that dwarfs the entire capital requirement of a competitor\'s refresh program. Eutelsat, by contrast, must dilute shareholders and accept state ownership to fund a program equal to ~3.3x its own annual EBITDA.\n\n**(b) Falcon 9 launch-cost advantage eliminates the largest external cost line.** The S-1 discloses that Falcon 9 reduced launch cost to ~$2,700/kg versus a historical average of $18,500/kg (an ~85% reduction), with boosters engineered for up to 40 flights (25-flight accounting life) and only the second stage expensed per launch. Critically, **Starlink launches are internal**: costs are capitalized to the Connectivity segment at marginal cost rather than purchased from a third-party launch provider at market rates. Eutelsat, lacking its own launch capability, must procure launches externally (historically via Arianespace/Soyuz and now including SpaceX itself), which is embedded in the €2.2B program cost. The S-1 explicitly states this is "an uneconomic proposition for those lacking an ability to deliver substantial mass into space." The 122 internal Starlink launches in 2025 (up from 89 in 2024) illustrate a refresh tempo that would be prohibitively expensive on external launch markets.\n\n**(c) Vertical integration compresses satellite unit economics.** SpaceX manufactures satellites entirely in-house at Redmond (bus, phased-array antennas, propulsion, solar arrays, inter-satellite lasers) and has reduced manufacturing cost per Gbps of downlink capacity by **3x from V1 to V2 Mini**, with a projected **9x reduction from V1 to V3**. Eutelsat\'s €2.2B/440-satellite program implies ~**€5M (~$5.8M) per satellite including launch** from Airbus — a price that reflects Airbus\'s profit margin and Eutelsat\'s lack of vertical integration. SpaceX captures that margin internally and reinvests it, which is why Connectivity capex of $4,178M funded ~3,100 satellites *plus* ground infrastructure *plus* user-terminal manufacturing scale-up (Bastrop producing tens of thousands of kits/day with a 59% cost reduction since 2022) — and still left $2,990M of segment free cash flow.\n\n### 5. Synthesis\n\nThe contrast is stark:\n\n| Dimension | Eutelsat (OneWeb refresh) | SpaceX (Starlink, FY2025 actual) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Program size | €2.2B (~$2.56B) over 5 years | ~3,100 satellites launched in 2025 alone |\n| Funding source | €1.5B equity + €1.0B sovereign-guaranteed ECA + €1.5B bond refinancing | Internal Connectivity-segment cash flow |\n| External dependencies | French/UK government backing; Airbus manufacturing; third-party launch | Fully internal (Redmond manufacturing + Falcon 9 launch) |\n| Balance-sheet impact | Net debt halved (€2.6B→€1.3B); required Moody\'s B1→Ba3 and Fitch B/CCC+→BB upgrades | $24.7B cash vs. $22.0B total debt principal; no equity raise needed |\n| EBITDA coverage of program | ~0.3x annual EBITDA per year of program (3.3x total) | ~5.8x annual FCF coverage of Eutelsat-equivalent annual cost; 1.17x of entire program in one year |\n| Sovereign / rating dependency | High — program viability contingent on state support and rating actions | None — self-funded at current run-rates |\n\n**Conclusion:** At FY2025 run-rates, Starlink\'s Connectivity segment generates sufficient free cash flow ($2,990M after $4,178M of capex) to fund an Eutelsat-equivalent 440-satellite refresh program **roughly 5.8 times over on an annual basis**, or the *entire* program in under a year — while simultaneously refreshing its own ~9,600-satellite constellation at a cadence ~7x faster than Eutelsat\'s planned program. Eutelsat\'s need for €1.5B of equity (with sovereign dilution), €1.0B of government-guaranteed export credit, €1.5B of bond refinancing, and credit-rating upgrades to execute a materially smaller program demonstrates that **the combination of (i) Starlink\'s revenue/subscriber scale, (ii) Falcon 9\'s reusable launch-cost structure (internalized at marginal cost), and (iii) end-to-end vertical integration of satellite manufacturing constitutes a structural competitive moat**. Competitors lacking internal launch and high-throughput in-house manufacturing cannot match Starlink\'s refresh economics without external capital, sovereign backing, and rating-dependent financing — exactly the dependencies Eutelsat\'s 2025–26 capital raise exposed.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA, capex, balance sheet, Falcon 9 launch economics, Starlink scale disclosures"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.spaceintelreport.com/eutelsat-continues-2-56-billion-oneweb-refurbishment-with-340-satellite-order-to-airbus-first-launches-in-2026",\n      "name": "Space Intel Report — Eutelsat\'s €2.2B ($2.56B) OneWeb refurbishment program with Airbus (440 satellites)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/starlink-rival-eutelsat-orders-340-oneweb-satellites-airbus-2026-01-12",\n      "name": "Reuters — Eutelsat orders 340 OneWeb satellites from Airbus (Jan 12, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://europeanspaceflight.com/eutelsat-to-raise-e1-5-billion-to-refinance-its-debt",\n      "name": "European Spaceflight — Eutelsat €1.5B capital raise, net debt €2.6B, 3.88x leverage"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://news.satnews.com/2025/12/02/moodys-upgrades-eutelsat",\n      "name": "SatNews — Moody\'s upgrades Eutelsat (B1→Ba3); leverage 3.9x→2.5x forecast"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.tradingview.com/news/reuters.com,2025-12-03:newsml_FIT6R0FfC:0-fitch-upgrades-eutelsat-to-bb-outlook-stable",\n      "name": "Fitch Ratings via TradingView — Eutelsat upgraded to BB from B; senior unsecured to BB from CCC+"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.ad-hoc-news.de/boerse/ueberblick/eutelsat-secures-major-debt-refinancing-with-1-5-billion-bond-issue/68610992",\n      "name": "ad-hoc-news — Eutelsat net debt halved to €1.3B, leverage 2.00x, €1B ECA financing, €1.5B bond refinancing"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/corporate/story/bharti-group-backed-eutelsat-eyes-strategic-lead-in-space-communications-with-eu135-billion-capital-raise-481218-2025-06-20",\n      "name": "Business Today — Eutelsat FY2025-26 capex guidance €1.0–1.1B, LEO expansion focus"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.exchange-rates.org/exchange-rate-history/eur-usd-2025-12-31",\n      "name": "Exchange-Rates.org — EUR/USD exchange rate history (Dec 2025 ≈ 1.17–1.18)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
2026-06-25 01:37:42,139 DEBUG Tool result: ToolCallRecord(
    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_4ee6c8018e994f37bb12f439',
        call_id=None,
        name='submit_final_result',
        args='{"final_result":"## Assessment: Starlink\'s Self-Funding Capacity vs. Eutelsat\'s Externally-Financed Constellation Refresh\\n\\n### 1. SpaceX Connectivity Segment FY2025 Cash Generation Profile (from S-1)\\n\\nPer the recast consolidated S-1 (which includes xAI and X Holdings for all periods presented), the Connectivity (Starlink) segment reported the following for FY2025:\\n\\n| Metric (FY2025) | Amount |\\n|---|---|\\n| Connectivity Segment Revenue | $11,387M |\\n| Connectivity Segment Income from Operations | $4,423M |\\n| (+) Depreciation & Amortization | $2,376M |\\n| (+) Share-based compensation | $369M |\\n| **Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$7,168M** |\\n| **Connectivity Segment Capex** | **$4,178M** |\\n| **EBITDA − Capex (FCF proxy)** | **$2,990M** |\\n\\nFor context, Connectivity Adjusted EBITDA grew from $1,602M (FY2023) → $3,849M (FY2024) → $7,168M (FY2025), an 86% YoY growth rate, while Connectivity capex grew more slowly ($2,455M → $3,498M → $4,178M, ~19% YoY in 2025). The segment is therefore not only large but expanding its cash conversion.\\n\\n### 2. Eutelsat\'s Funding Structure for the 440-Satellite Refresh\\n\\nEutelsat\'s OneWeb Gen-1 replenishment program (440 satellites ordered from Airbus, deliveries beginning late 2026) carries an estimated total cost of **€2.2 billion (≈ $2.56 billion at ~1.16 EUR/USD)** spread over 2024–2029 — i.e., roughly **€440M (~$512M) per year** over five years. (Note: the question\'s phrasing of \\"€2.56 billion\\" appears to conflate the euro-denominated program cost of €2.2B with its USD-equivalent of ~$2.56B; the underlying program size is €2.2B.)\\n\\nTo execute this program, Eutelsat required a layered external financing structure:\\n\\n| Funding Component | Amount | Source / Character |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Equity capital raise (H1 FY2025-26) | €1.5B | French State (stake to ~29.65%), UK, Bharti, CMA CGM, FSP — significant dilution / state ownership |\\n| Government-backed export credit financing (Feb 2026) | ~€1.0B | French government-guaranteed, dedicated to LEO satellites |\\n| Bond refinancing | €1.5B | Replaced higher-cost debt |\\n| **Result: Net debt halved** | €2.6B → €1.3B | Net debt/EBITDA from 3.88x → ~2.00x |\\n| **Credit rating upgrades required** | Moody\'s: B1 → Ba3; Fitch: B/CCC+ → BB | Triggered by the raise |\\n\\nEutelsat\'s standalone EBITDA is approximately **€650–670M** (implied from net debt/EBITDA ratios), against which the €2.2B program represents **~3.3x annual EBITDA** — a multi-year commitment that could not be absorbed internally and required sovereign-backed support and rating actions to make viable.\\n\\n### 3. Could Starlink Self-Fund an Equivalent Refresh at Current Run-Rates?\\n\\n**Yes — and by a wide margin.** Using SpaceX\'s disclosed FY2025 Connectivity figures:\\n\\n- **Annual FCF proxy (EBITDA − Capex): $2,990M**\\n- **Eutelsat-equivalent annual program cost: ~$512M/year** (€2.2B / 5 years)\\n- **Coverage ratio: $2,990M / $512M ≈ 5.8x**\\n\\nEven on a total-program basis, **one year of Connectivity-segment free cash flow ($2,990M) covers 117% of the entire $2.56B Eutelsat program** ($2,990M / $2,560M = 1.17x). Put differently, Starlink\'s FY2025 cash generation after capex could fund the *entire* 440-satellite OneWeb refresh in under 11 months — without touching the $24.7B of consolidated cash on the balance sheet, without issuing equity, and without sovereign credit support.\\n\\nThis comparison is, if anything, conservative because:\\n- SpaceX is *already* refreshing its constellation at a far higher cadence: **~3,100 Starlink satellites launched in 2025** (vs. Eutelsat\'s 440 over five years), with a Redmond production line running at **~70 satellites/week (~3,640/year)**.\\n- The $4,178M of Connectivity capex in FY2025 *already includes* the cost of manufacturing and internally launching those 3,100 satellites (the S-1 confirms Starlink-dedicated launch costs are capitalized within the Connectivity segment, not recognized as Space-segment revenue). The $2,990M FCF proxy is therefore *after* funding a refresh rate roughly **7x faster** than Eutelsat\'s planned program.\\n- SpaceX\'s constellation is ~9,600 satellites (≈75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit) versus OneWeb\'s ~648 — meaning Starlink\'s refresh burden in absolute terms is far larger, yet is absorbed entirely within segment cash flow.\\n\\n### 4. What the Contrast Reveals About Starlink\'s Competitive Moat\\n\\nThe funding-structure divergence between the two operators isolates three reinforcing layers of Starlink\'s moat:\\n\\n**(a) Scale of cash generation.** SpaceX\'s Connectivity segment alone generated **$7,168M of Adjusted EBITDA in FY2025** — roughly **10.7x Eutelsat\'s total company EBITDA (~€670M)** — off a 10.3M-subscriber base across 164 markets. This revenue scale (driven by 104.7% subscriber growth, partially offset by 22.9% ARPU decline from international expansion) produces operating cash flow that dwarfs the entire capital requirement of a competitor\'s refresh program. Eutelsat, by contrast, must dilute shareholders and accept state ownership to fund a program equal to ~3.3x its own annual EBITDA.\\n\\n**(b) Falcon 9 launch-cost advantage eliminates the largest external cost line.** The S-1 discloses that Falcon 9 reduced launch cost to ~$2,700/kg versus a historical average of $18,500/kg (an ~85% reduction), with boosters engineered for up to 40 flights (25-flight accounting life) and only the second stage expensed per launch. Critically, **Starlink launches are internal**: costs are capitalized to the Connectivity segment at marginal cost rather than purchased from a third-party launch provider at market rates. Eutelsat, lacking its own launch capability, must procure launches externally (historically via Arianespace/Soyuz and now including SpaceX itself), which is embedded in the €2.2B program cost. The S-1 explicitly states this is \\"an uneconomic proposition for those lacking an ability to deliver substantial mass into space.\\" The 122 internal Starlink launches in 2025 (up from 89 in 2024) illustrate a refresh tempo that would be prohibitively expensive on external launch markets.\\n\\n**(c) Vertical integration compresses satellite unit economics.** SpaceX manufactures satellites entirely in-house at Redmond (bus, phased-array antennas, propulsion, solar arrays, inter-satellite lasers) and has reduced manufacturing cost per Gbps of downlink capacity by **3x from V1 to V2 Mini**, with a projected **9x reduction from V1 to V3**. Eutelsat\'s €2.2B/440-satellite program implies ~**€5M (~$5.8M) per satellite including launch** from Airbus — a price that reflects Airbus\'s profit margin and Eutelsat\'s lack of vertical integration. SpaceX captures that margin internally and reinvests it, which is why Connectivity capex of $4,178M funded ~3,100 satellites *plus* ground infrastructure *plus* user-terminal manufacturing scale-up (Bastrop producing tens of thousands of kits/day with a 59% cost reduction since 2022) — and still left $2,990M of segment free cash flow.\\n\\n### 5. Synthesis\\n\\nThe contrast is stark:\\n\\n| Dimension | Eutelsat (OneWeb refresh) | SpaceX (Starlink, FY2025 actual) |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Program size | €2.2B (~$2.56B) over 5 years | ~3,100 satellites launched in 2025 alone |\\n| Funding source | €1.5B equity + €1.0B sovereign-guaranteed ECA + €1.5B bond refinancing | Internal Connectivity-segment cash flow |\\n| External dependencies | French/UK government backing; Airbus manufacturing; third-party launch | Fully internal (Redmond manufacturing + Falcon 9 launch) |\\n| Balance-sheet impact | Net debt halved (€2.6B→€1.3B); required Moody\'s B1→Ba3 and Fitch B/CCC+→BB upgrades | $24.7B cash vs. $22.0B total debt principal; no equity raise needed |\\n| EBITDA coverage of program | ~0.3x annual EBITDA per year of program (3.3x total) | ~5.8x annual FCF coverage of Eutelsat-equivalent annual cost; 1.17x of entire program in one year |\\n| Sovereign / rating dependency | High — program viability contingent on state support and rating actions | None — self-funded at current run-rates |\\n\\n**Conclusion:** At FY2025 run-rates, Starlink\'s Connectivity segment generates sufficient free cash flow ($2,990M after $4,178M of capex) to fund an Eutelsat-equivalent 440-satellite refresh program **roughly 5.8 times over on an annual basis**, or the *entire* program in under a year — while simultaneously refreshing its own ~9,600-satellite constellation at a cadence ~7x faster than Eutelsat\'s planned program. Eutelsat\'s need for €1.5B of equity (with sovereign dilution), €1.0B of government-guaranteed export credit, €1.5B of bond refinancing, and credit-rating upgrades to execute a materially smaller program demonstrates that **the combination of (i) Starlink\'s revenue/subscriber scale, (ii) Falcon 9\'s reusable launch-cost structure (internalized at marginal cost), and (iii) end-to-end vertical integration of satellite manufacturing constitutes a structural competitive moat**. Competitors lacking internal launch and high-throughput in-house manufacturing cannot match Starlink\'s refresh economics without external capital, sovereign backing, and rating-dependent financing — exactly the dependencies Eutelsat\'s 2025–26 capital raise exposed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Sources\\n\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA, capex, balance sheet, Falcon 9 launch economics, Starlink scale disclosures\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.spaceintelreport.com/eutelsat-continues-2-56-billion-oneweb-refurbishment-with-340-satellite-order-to-airbus-first-launches-in-2026\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"Space Intel Report — Eutelsat\'s €2.2B ($2.56B) OneWeb refurbishment program with Airbus (440 satellites)\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/starlink-rival-eutelsat-orders-340-oneweb-satellites-airbus-2026-01-12\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"Reuters — Eutelsat orders 340 OneWeb satellites from Airbus (Jan 12, 2026)\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://europeanspaceflight.com/eutelsat-to-raise-e1-5-billion-to-refinance-its-debt\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"European Spaceflight — Eutelsat €1.5B capital raise, net debt €2.6B, 3.88x leverage\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://news.satnews.com/2025/12/02/moodys-upgrades-eutelsat\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SatNews — Moody\'s upgrades Eutelsat (B1→Ba3); leverage 3.9x→2.5x forecast\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.tradingview.com/news/reuters.com,2025-12-03:newsml_FIT6R0FfC:0-fitch-upgrades-eutelsat-to-bb-outlook-stable\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"Fitch Ratings via TradingView — Eutelsat upgraded to BB from B; senior unsecured to BB from CCC+\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.ad-hoc-news.de/boerse/ueberblick/eutelsat-secures-major-debt-refinancing-with-1-5-billion-bond-issue/68610992\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"ad-hoc-news — Eutelsat net debt halved to €1.3B, leverage 2.00x, €1B ECA financing, €1.5B bond refinancing\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/corporate/story/bharti-group-backed-eutelsat-eyes-strategic-lead-in-space-communications-with-eu135-billion-capital-raise-481218-2025-06-20\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"Business Today — Eutelsat FY2025-26 capex guidance €1.0–1.1B, LEO expansion focus\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.exchange-rates.org/exchange-rate-history/eur-usd-2025-12-31\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"Exchange-Rates.org — EUR/USD exchange rate history (Dec 2025 ≈ 1.17–1.18)\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
