rnal Starlink launches in 2025 (up from 89 in 2024) illustrate a refresh tempo that would be prohibitively expensive on external launch markets.\n\n**(c) Vertical integration compresses satellite unit economics.** SpaceX manufactures satellites entirely in-house at Redmond (bus, phased-array antennas, propulsion, solar arrays, inter-satellite lasers) and has reduced manufacturing cost per Gbps of downlink capacity by **3x from V1 to V2 Mini**, with a projected **9x reduction from V1 to V3**. Eutelsat\'s €2.2B/440-satellite program implies ~**€5M (~$5.8M) per satellite including launch** from Airbus — a price that reflects Airbus\'s profit margin and Eutelsat\'s lack of vertical integration. SpaceX captures that margin internally and reinvests it, which is why Connectivity capex of $4,178M funded ~3,100 satellites *plus* ground infrastructure *plus* user-terminal manufacturing scale-up (Bastrop producing tens of thousands of kits/day with a 59% cost reduction since 2022) — and still left $2,990M of segment free cash flow.\n\n### 5. Synthesis\n\nThe contrast is stark:\n\n| Dimension | Eutelsat (OneWeb refresh) | SpaceX (Starlink, FY2025 actual) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Program size | €2.2B (~$2.56B) over 5 years | ~3,100 satellites launched in 2025 alone |\n| Funding source | €1.5B equity + €1.0B sovereign-guaranteed ECA + €1.5B bond refinancing | Internal Connectivity-segment cash flow |\n| External dependencies | French/UK government backing; Airbus manufacturing; third-party launch | Fully internal (Redmond manufacturing + Falcon 9 launch) |\n| Balance-sheet impact | Net debt halved (€2.6B→€1.3B); required Moody\'s B1→Ba3 and Fitch B/CCC+→BB upgrades | $24.7B cash vs. $22.0B total debt principal; no equity raise needed |\n| EBITDA coverage of program | ~0.3x annual EBITDA per year of program (3.3x total) | ~5.8x annual FCF coverage of Eutelsat-equivalent annual cost; 1.17x of entire program in one year |\n| Sovereign / rating dependency | High — program viability contingent on state support and rating actions | None — self-funded at current run-rates |\n\n**Conclusion:** At FY2025 run-rates, Starlink\'s Connectivity segment generates sufficient free cash flow ($2,990M after $4,178M of capex) to fund an Eutelsat-equivalent 440-satellite refresh program **roughly 5.8 times over on an annual basis**, or the *entire* program in under a year — while simultaneously refreshing its own ~9,600-satellite constellation at a cadence ~7x faster than Eutelsat\'s planned program. Eutelsat\'s need for €1.5B of equity (with sovereign dilution), €1.0B of government-guaranteed export credit, €1.5B of bond refinancing, and credit-rating upgrades to execute a materially smaller program demonstrates that **the combination of (i) Starlink\'s revenue/subscriber scale, (ii) Falcon 9\'s reusable launch-cost structure (internalized at marginal cost), and (iii) end-to-end vertical integration of satellite manufacturing constitutes a structural competitive moat**. Competitors lacking internal launch and high-throughput in-house manufacturing cannot match Starlink\'s refresh economics without external capital, sovereign backing, and rating-dependent financing — exactly the dependencies Eutelsat\'s 2025–26 capital raise exposed.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA, capex, balance sheet, Falcon 9 launch economics, Starlink scale disclosures"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.spaceintelreport.com/eutelsat-continues-2-56-billion-oneweb-refurbishment-with-340-satellite-order-to-airbus-first-launches-in-2026",\n      "name": "Space Intel Report — Eutelsat\'s €2.2B ($2.56B) OneWeb refurbishment program with Airbus (440 satellites)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/starlink-rival-eu